  "why": "The paper provides partial diagnostic insight by characterizing properties and patterns of the discovered failures (e.g., which mutation types cause most failures, examples showing occlusion/perspective/lighting issues, per-SUT inconsistency counts, and manual inspection / false-positive rates). However, it does not trace failures to underlying model vulnerabilities such as biased or corrupted training data, spurious features, or internal model behavior (activations) nor propose root-cause remedies. The authors themselves note that further analysis of specific SUTs is needed to understand the factors involved.",
  "evidence": "6.4.1 RQ1 Results (p.1966): \"1210 SUT inconsistencies resulting from 884 mutations and that each SUT had over 100 inconsistencies.\"; (p.1966, Fig.12 discussion) \"the leftmost column shows a moderate inconsistency; an added person occludes a bus, causing EfficientPS to then classify the bus as a train.\" — an explicit characterization linking an input pattern (occlusion) to misclassification. 6.4.3 RQ3 Results (p.1967): \"The add car mutation induced the most inconsistencies (877), followed by the add person mutation (280), and then the mutation to change the car color (53). ... This suggests that editing large regions of the image, even in a conforming manner, is insufficient. This further supports our notion that high level semantic mutations such as adding a car are required to exercise these perception systems and find inconsistencies.\" 4.3.2 Potential for False Positives (p.1963): \"Figure 9a shows an example of a car that has been added to an image with a perspective mismatch... Figure 9b shows an instance where a car has been added on top of a person... Figure 9c [and 9d] ... inconsistent lighting ... missing shadow.\" 6.4.1 (p.1966–1967): \"To gain a better grasp on the rate of false positives we manually inspect all the generated test cases that led to 5+ p.p. drop... The process entailed each author examining each image... If any of the three authors deemed an image a false positive, it was conservatively recorded as such.\" and Table 2 (p.1967) reports false positive rates per SUT. Negative evidence (lack of root-cause linking to model internals) (p.1966): \"Further analysis of the specific SUTs is needed to understand the factors involved in this performance, but these data suggest that the highest performing SUTs may be more brittle under certain conditions.\""
